diff:1669665056:1669605969:=52,70c52%0a%3c #foxbegin 221128-195057-909060#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!A Comparison to ASL %0a%3c -> - drjiang%0a%3c -> [-28.11.2022 - 11:50-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221128-195057-909060 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c The wiki mentions that English Sign Language originated before Chinese Sign language, yet how do the two differ? The below article delves into the differences between how the differences in the spoken Chinese and English languages and cultures impact the changes in their respective sign languages. The article places emphasis on how small differences such as having an outstretched thumb instead of a curled on in the typical ASL fist show up between Chinese Sign language and American ones. The article determines that American sign language is much more constrained to its original rules while Chinese sign language is more flexible and varies among the different familiarities of Speakers. For example, Chinese sign language users who also know American Sign language would sign differently as to those who only learned Chinese sign language.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c https://lcn.salk.edu/publications/SOL/SOL%2520-%25206%2520Chinese%2520vs%2520American%2520Signs.pdf%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221128-195057-909060#%0a---%0a> %0a
